## React 19 `use()` Hook

### Unwrap a Promise (suspends automatically)
```tsx
import { use, Suspense } from 'react';

// Pass a promise (NOT called inside component — created outside or cached)
function UserCard({ userPromise }: { userPromise: Promise<User> }) {
  const user = use(userPromise); // suspends until resolved
  return <div>{user.name}</div>;
}

function Page() {
  const userPromise = fetchUser('1'); // created in Server Component or stable ref
  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Skeleton />}>
      <UserCard userPromise={userPromise} />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

### Unwrap Context (conditionally, unlike useContext)
```tsx
import { use } from 'react';

function Button({ children }) {
  // use() can be called in conditionals/loops — useContext cannot
  if (someCondition) {
    const theme = use(ThemeContext);
    return <button className={theme.btn}>{children}</button>;
  }
  return <button>{children}</button>;
}
```

**Key rules:**
- `use()` can be called conditionally — `useContext`/`useState` cannot
- Promise passed to `use()` must be stable (don't create inline in render)
- Always pair with `<Suspense>` and `<ErrorBoundary>`

## `useActionState`

### With Server Action (Next.js App Router)
```ts
// actions/user.ts
'use server';
import { z } from 'zod';

type State = { errors?: { name?: string[]; email?: string[] }; message?: string } | null;

export async function createUser(prevState: State, formData: FormData): Promise<State> {
  const result = schema.safeParse(Object.fromEntries(formData));
  if (!result.success) return { errors: result.error.flatten().fieldErrors };
  await db.users.create({ data: result.data });
  return { message: 'User created' };
}
```

```tsx
// components/CreateUserForm.tsx
'use client';
import { useActionState } from 'react';
import { createUser } from '@/actions/user';

export function CreateUserForm() {
  const [state, action, isPending] = useActionState(createUser, null);

  return (
    <form action={action}>  {/* native form action — works without JS */}
      <input name="name" aria-invalid={!!state?.errors?.name} />
      {state?.errors?.name && <p>{state.errors.name[0]}</p>}

      <input name="email" type="email" aria-invalid={!!state?.errors?.email} />
      {state?.errors?.email && <p>{state.errors.email[0]}</p>}

      <button disabled={isPending}>
        {isPending ? 'Creating...' : 'Create User'}
      </button>
      {state?.message && <p>{state.message}</p>}
    </form>
  );
}
```

**Why:** Progressive enhancement — form works without JS. `isPending` gives instant feedback.

## `useOptimistic`

```tsx
'use client';
import { useOptimistic, useTransition } from 'react';
import { toggleTodo } from '@/actions/todos';

function TodoList({ todos }: { todos: Todo[] }) {
  const [optimisticTodos, setOptimisticTodos] = useOptimistic(
    todos,
    (currentTodos, updatedId: string) =>
      currentTodos.map(t => t.id === updatedId ? { ...t, done: !t.done } : t)
  );

  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();

  function handleToggle(id: string) {
    startTransition(async () => {
      setOptimisticTodos(id);   // apply optimistic update immediately
      await toggleTodo(id);     // actual server action
      // On complete: optimisticTodos reverts to real `todos` prop
    });
  }

  return (
    <ul>
      {optimisticTodos.map(todo => (
        <li key={todo.id} style={{ opacity: isPending ? 0.7 : 1 }}>
          <button onClick={() => handleToggle(todo.id)}>
            {todo.done ? '✓' : '○'} {todo.text}
          </button>
        </li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

**How it works:**
1. `useOptimistic` shows the optimistic value during the transition
2. When the parent re-renders with new `todos` (from `revalidatePath`), the optimistic state is discarded
3. If the Server Action throws, React automatically reverts to the previous state

## `useTransition` for Mutations

```tsx
'use client';
import { useTransition } from 'react';
import { deleteUser } from '@/actions/users';
import { useRouter } from 'next/navigation';

function DeleteButton({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const [isPending, startTransition] = useTransition();
  const router = useRouter();

  function handleDelete() {
    startTransition(async () => {
      await deleteUser(userId);
      router.push('/users');   // navigation inside transition = non-blocking
    });
  }

  return (
    <button onClick={handleDelete} disabled={isPending}>
      {isPending ? 'Deleting...' : 'Delete'}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### useTransition vs useActionState
| Feature | `useTransition` | `useActionState` |
|---------|----------------|------------------|
| Manages pending state | ✅ | ✅ |
| Returns action errors/data | ❌ | ✅ |
| Native `<form action={}>` | ❌ | ✅ |
| Progressive enhancement | ❌ | ✅ |
| Multiple actions | ✅ | ❌ |

**Rule:** Use `useActionState` for forms. Use `useTransition` for non-form mutations (button clicks, drag-drop, etc.).

## React Compiler

### Setup (Next.js 15+)
```bash
npm install -D babel-plugin-react-compiler
```

```ts
// next.config.ts
export default {
  experimental: { reactCompiler: true },
};
```

### What it replaces
```tsx
// BEFORE compiler
const expensiveValue = useMemo(() => compute(a, b), [a, b]);
const handleClick   = useCallback(() => onClick(id), [id, onClick]);
const MemoChild     = memo(ChildComponent);

// AFTER compiler — just write normal code
const expensiveValue = compute(a, b); // compiler memoizes automatically
const handleClick   = () => onClick(id);
function ChildComponent(props) { ... } // compiler decides if memo needed
```

### Rules of React (required for compiler)
```tsx
// WRONG — mutation in render
function Bad({ items }) {
  items.push('new'); // mutates prop — compiler can't optimize
  return <List items={items} />;
}

// CORRECT — new array
function Good({ items }) {
  const updated = [...items, 'new'];
  return <List items={updated} />;
}
```

### Escape hatch
```tsx
function LegacyComponent() {
  'use no memo';  // opt out this component from compiler optimization
  // use when: third-party libs that depend on reference equality tricks
}
```

**Adoption:** Start with `eslint-plugin-react-compiler` to find violations, fix, then enable compiler.

## RSC Mental Model

### The two trees
```
Server tree (zero client JS)     Client tree ('use client')
─────────────────────────────    ──────────────────────────
Layout (server)                  InteractiveNav (client)
  ├─ Nav (server)                  useState, useEffect OK
  ├─ Sidebar (server)              event handlers OK
  └─ Page (server)                 browser APIs OK
       └─ ProductCard (server)     
            └─ AddToCart (client)  ← leaf-level interactivity
```

### Data fetching at the leaf
```tsx
// WRONG — fetching in root, prop-drilling data down
async function Page() {
  const user = await getUser();
  return <Layout user={user}><Content user={user} /></Layout>;
}

// CORRECT — each component fetches what IT needs
async function UserAvatar({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  const user = await getUser(userId); // fetch exactly here
  return <img src={user.avatar} alt={user.name} />;
}
// Parallel fetches — Next.js deduplicates via fetch cache
```

### Passing Server Components INTO Client Components
```tsx
// CORRECT — children prop threads server output through client
'use client';
function Carousel({ children }) {  // children = Server Component output
  const [idx, setIdx] = useState(0);
  return <div>{children[idx]}</div>;
}

// page.tsx (Server Component)
<Carousel>
  {items.map(item => <ItemCard key={item.id} data={item} />)}
</Carousel>
```

**Rule:** `'use client'` marks a boundary, not a single component. Everything below it is also a Client Component unless explicitly re-imported as server.
